"England":"England","BRETON":"Breton, Plaquemines, Louisiana, United States","Chigwell, Essex, England":"Chigwell, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"BRETON","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Normand, Renald, Adelard, Alphonse, Armand, Gaetan, Laurent, Serge, Adrien, Aime.","French, Breton (mainly Finistère), and English (of Norman origin): ethnic name for a Breton, from Old French <i>breton</i>, oblique case of <i>bret</i> (see   Bret  ). Compare   Lebreton  , see also English   Brett  .","History: In North America, this surname was originally also a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Jean Élie/Hélie <i>dit</i> (Le) Breton from Ménéac in Morbihan, Brittany (France), who married Jeanne Labbé in Sainte-Famille, Île d'Orléans, QC, in 1669. His descendants also bear the surname   Elie  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bret","meanings":["French: ethnic name for a Breton, from Old French <i>bret</i>, nominative of <i>breton</i> ‘Breton’ (see   Breton  ). See also English   Brett  ."]},{"name":"Brittain","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Anglo-Norman French <i>Bretagne</i>, <i>Bretaign(e)</i> ‘Brittany’. Some of the modern forms are from the Middle English <i>Brytane</i>, <i>Brittan</i> ‘Breton’; compare   Breton  ."]},{"name":"Britton","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Breton  , and ethnic name for a Breton, from Old French <i>Breton</i>, the oblique case form of Old French <i>Bret</i>; compare   Brittain   and   Brett  ."]},{"name":"Bretton","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: variant of   Breton  .","English: habitational name from any of the places called from Bretton in Derbyshire and Yorkshire, both of which mean ‘settlement of the Britons’, from Old English <i>Brettas</i> ‘Briton’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."]}]},{"name":"Ralf","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Chigwell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from a local name deriving from Old English  <i>cis</i> or  <i>cisel</i> ‘pebble(s), gravel’ +  <i>w(i)elle</i>,  <i>w(i)ella</i> ‘stream, spring’, but possible place-name sources in Dorset, Herts, Kent, and Shrops are recorded only late in relevant spellings, and the place or places cannot be identified."],"variants":[]},{"name":"BRITO","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["contracted form of <i>Birgit</i> (  see  Bridget  ), made famous in the English-speaking world by the Swedish actress  Britt Ekland  (  b. 1942 ; her surname was originally  Eklund )."],"variants":[{"name":"Birgit","meanings":["Borrowing of the Irish name <i>Brighid</i> (  see  Bridget   ). This name owes its enormous popularity in Scandinavia, especially in Sweden, to  St Birgitta  (  1304–73 ), patron saint of Sweden. She was a noblewoman who bore her husband eight children. After his death, she founded an order of nuns, the ‘Bridgettines’ or Order of the Most Holy Saviour. She also went to Rome, where she attempted to reform religious life."]}]},{"name":"LE","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Profit’ or ‘sharp’.","2  ♀, ♂ ‘Upright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ralf of Chigwell BRITO LE BRETON was born about 1125, in Breton, Plaquemines, Louisiana, United States, his father, Richard Breton, was 27 and his mother, Breton, was 25. He had at least 1 son with de Foliot. He died before April 1185, in Chigwell, Essex, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"um 1125–before April 1185":"umbes 1125–enne aprilli 1185","1125–1185":"1125–1185","1127–Male":"1127–Surnud","1133–Female":"1133–Surnud","1127–Female":"1127–Surnud","1150–1199":"1150–1199","1152–Male":"1152–Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1102–Female":"1102–Surnud","about 1150":"umbes 1150","before April 1185":"enne aprilli 1185","1152":"1152","1185":"1185","1150":"1150","1127":"1127","1125":"1125","1102":"1102","um 1152":"umbes 1152","1100":"1100","1199":"1199","1133":"1133","um 1125":"umbes 1125","England":"England","BRETON":"Breton, Plaquemines, Louisiana, Ameerika Ühendriigid","Chigwell, Essex, England":"Chigwell, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"um 1125–before April 1185":"noin 1125–ennen vuotta huhtikuu 1185","1125–1185":"1125–1185","1127–Male":"1127–Kuollut","1133–Female":"1133–Kuollut","1127–Female":"1127–Kuollut","1150–1199":"1150–1199","1152–Male":"1152–Kuollut","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1102–Female":"1102–Kuollut","about 1150":"noin 1150","before April 1185":"ennen vuotta huhtikuu 1185","1152":"1152","1185":"1185","1150":"1150","1127":"1127","1125":"1125","1102":"1102","um 1152":"noin 1152","1100":"1100","1199":"1199","1133":"1133","um 1125":"noin 1125","England":"England","BRETON":"Breton, Plaquemines, Louisiana, Yhdysvallat","Chigwell, Essex, England":"Chigwell, Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"um 1125–before April 1185":"environ 1125–avant avril 1185","1125–1185":"1125–1185","1127–Male":"1127–Décédé","1133–Female":"1133–Décédée","1127–Female":"1127–Décédée","1150–1199":"1150–1199","1152–Male":"1152–Décéd